   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "806f05cc",
   "source": "## Implementation Plan — Q1: Outlier Detection & Interpretation\n\n### 1. Univariate Analysis (Z-Score)\nCompute z-scores for `price`, `average_playtime`, `median_playtime`, `positive_ratings`, `negative_ratings` independently. Flag any game exceeding |z| > 3. Report flagged titles per attribute.\n\n---\n\n### 2. Outlier Distribution Analysis\nFor each attribute's flagged outliers, characterize what they likely represent:\n\n**Random noise**\n- Outliers are sparse, z-scores cluster just beyond the threshold (3–4σ), no meaningful pattern in the flagged titles.\n- Implementation: histogram of z-scores for flagged points — if roughly uniform with no heavy tail, noise is the likely story.\n\n**Clustering (market phenomenon)**\n- Outliers group together — e.g., a band of free-to-play games with massive playtime, or AAA titles with very high prices.\n- Implementation: run DBSCAN on the 1D outlier z-scores (or 2D with a second attribute) and check whether >1 dense cluster emerges vs. all points being noise-labeled.\n\n**Data error**\n- Extreme z-scores far beyond the rest (e.g., >10σ), or values that are logically impossible (price = $0 with owners = 0, playtime values in the millions).\n- Implementation: hard threshold on z-score magnitude (e.g., flag |z| > 8 separately) and sanity checks on value ranges.\n\n**Known distribution (power law / log-normal)**\n- Many engagement metrics on platforms follow a power law — a small number of titles capture disproportionate playtime or reviews. If outliers simply sit on the tail of such a distribution they are not anomalous, just expected extremes.\n- Implementation: fit `scipy.stats.powerlaw` and `scipy.stats.lognorm` to the full attribute distribution, overlay on histogram, compute KS-test p-value. If the fit is good, the \"outliers\" are the expected tail rather than anomalies.\n\n---\n\n### 3. Multivariate Outlier Detection (Isolation Forest)\nTrain an Isolation Forest on the numeric feature set: `price`, `average_playtime`, `median_playtime`, `positive_ratings`, `negative_ratings`, `owners` (parse midpoint from range string). Use anomaly scores to rank all games; flag the bottom 1–2% (most anomalous).\n\n---\n\n### 4. Multivariate Outlier Classification\nFor each Isolation Forest flagged game, explain *which combination of features* makes it anomalous:\n- Compute per-feature z-scores for the flagged point and sort by magnitude — the top contributors form a human-readable explanation (e.g., \"high playtime + low price + low ratings\").\n- Group flagged games by their dominant deviation pattern to surface recurring phenomena vs. one-off oddities.\n- Cross-reference with univariate outliers: points flagged by both are the strongest candidates for meaningful market phenomena; points only caught by Isolation Forest are combination anomalies worth investigating separately.\n",
